nd how they evolved over time - is thus crucial for our understanding of the lived experience of past generations and the physical environments which they inhabited. But studies of past agricultural regimes which are detailed enough to highlight their full social, economic and environmental character and implications, are surprisingly thin on the ground. This innovative book dissects the character of one key example - the foldcourse system of East Anglia - from its genesis in the early Middle Ages to its demise in the nineteenth century. It casts a mass of new light on an institution that structured rural life in one region of England, over many centuries. But it also provides important new insights into the nature of early farming systems more generally, and the intricate balance of human agency, and environmental structures, that shaped and sustained them. JOHN BELCHER gained his PhD in Landscape History from the University of East Anglia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAgricultural systemsxHistoryzEnglandzEast Anglia. 0aGrazingxHistoryzEnglandzEast Anglia. 0aSheepxFeeding and feedsxHistoryzEnglandzEast Anglia. 4aBritish Local History. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aMedieval History. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aDomesday book and East Anglia.  aNorfolk.  aSuffolk.  aagricultural improvement.  aagriculture.  acorn.  amanorial rights.  arural.  asheep.  asocial structures.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800101333?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800101333423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800101333/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyte